          "correctOptionId": "opt-1",
          "explanation": "Ans. B. CDKN2AThe cyclin-dependent kinase (CDK) inhibitor 2A gene (CDKN2A), located on chromosome 9p21, is the best-established high-risk locus for melanoma susceptibility.* In melanoma, tumor suppressors that play a protective role against melanoma are mutated.* CDKN2A encodes via alternative splicing for two proteins involved in cell cycle regulation: pl6/Ink4a and pl4/Arf, both act as tumor suppressors through the Rb and p53 cancer pathways, respectively.* CDKN2A mutations are found in approximately 40% of individuals with familial melanoma.",
